3d.title: What is Arbital?
3d.text:
Arbital takes the best from Wikipedia (wiki software) and Medium (blogging software) to create a website dedicated to discovering the truth.

Wikipedia is an online encyclopedia and focuses on presenting existing knowledge. Arbital, on the other hand, is a platform designed to help you discuss and generate *new* knowledge; to explore the frontiers of medicine, economics, and other disciplines.

Medium, like all blogging platforms, allows your posts to fade completely into oblivion after a few weeks. Arbital, on the other hand, embeds your blog posts in a web of links, so that your posts from many years ago can still be found and read by millions of people today.

Arbital allows you to express your opinion in two ways: liking and probability voting. Liking something rewards the author with karma for generating high quality content. Probability voting allows you to express your beliefs and work together with others to come up with accurate probability estimates. Example: [Vitamin D is good for you][1].

Arbital has a hierarchical system of organizing pages so you can find pages and explore topics easier. For example, see the page on [Vitamin D][2] along with all the children pages it has.


  [1]: http://zanaduu3.appspot.com/pages/1h
  [6]: http://zanaduu3.appspot.com/pages/VitaminD-1
